<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 10:20 p.m. EST  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	'Life is Beautiful' Best Foreign Film  
</P>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Robert Benigni's 'Life is Beautiful' got the  
nod as the best foreign film during tonight's Academy Awards. The 
Italian director wrote, directed and starred in the tragicomedy 
about a father who protects his son from the horrors of the 
Holocaust. Earlier, Judi Dench, who played the imperious but 
fair-minded Queen Elizabeth I in ``Shakespeare in Love,'' and James 
Coburn, the alcoholic, abusive father in ``Affliction,'' won best 
supporting Oscars. 

</P>
<P>
	Ex-Hostage Anderson Suing Iran  
</P>
<P>
	ATHENS, Ohio (AP) -- Terry Anderson is set to sue Iran for $100  
million over the more than six years the former Associated Press 
correspondent was held hostage, shackled and blindfolded, in 
Lebanon. The lawsuit accuses Iran of having sponsored his captors. 
The lawsuit, to be filed tomorrow, is also likely to become a 
challenge to the U.S. government. The Clinton administration has 
thwarted plaintiffs in similar lawsuits from collecting millions of 
dollars awarded by U.S. courts. Anderson was taken captive in 
Beirut on March 16, 1985, and was freed 2,454 days later, on Dec. 
4, 1991. 

</P>
<P>
	U.S. Making Last Kosovo Peace Effort  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Hours before a last-ditch diplomatic peace  
effort is to be made in Kosovo, a top Yugoslav Army general said 
his troops are ready ``to repel any aggression against our 
country.'' The U.S. is sending special envoy Richard Holbrooke to 
meet with Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic tomorrow night. 
Airstrikes are likely to follow if the talks end with Milosevic 
defiant on two counts: still refusing a Kosovo peace plan and 
persisting in pressing an offensive against outgunned Kosovo 
rebels. 

</P>
<P>
	Ex-Press Secretary Reedy Dies  
</P>
<P>
	MILWAUKEE (AP) -- George Reedy, former press secretary for  
President Lyndon Johnson who quit after disagreeing with Johnson's 
Vietnam War policies, died today at 81. Reedy died after a short 
illness at a Milwaukee nursing home where he had been living, an 
employee said. After working for UPI in Washington, D.C., Reedy 
joined the U.S. Senate staff of Johnson, a Texas Democrat, in 1951. 
Reedy stayed with Johnson, only to break away in 1966 over 
disagreements about Johnson's pursuit of the Vietnam War. 

</P>
<P>
	Train Crash Statements May Conflict  
</P>
<P>
	BOURBONNAIS, Ill. (AP) -- Witnesses to the deadly Amtrak train  
crash may have given conflicting statements about whether a 
steel-laden truck was on the tracks before warning signals and 
crossing gates activated. ``We have not been able to completely 
reconcile the statements that are possibly conflicting,'' said 
National Transportation Safety Board spokesman Jamie Finch. He 
would not comment on what the possible conflicts were. Eleven 
people were killed and more than 100 injured in when the Amtrak 
train crashed into the truck on March 15. 

</P>
<P>
	Chechen Leader Targeted by Mine  
</P>
<P>
	GROZNY, Russia (AP) -- A mine exploded near Chechen President  
Aslan Maskhadov's motorcade today in an assassination attempt while 
he was returning to his residence. Maskhadov was not hurt. One 
person was killed and eight were wounded by the radio-controlled 
device, said the president's press secretary, according to the 
Interfax news agency. It was the second explosion to rock the 
troubled Caucasus region in just three days. At least 51 people 
were killed in an explosion Friday at a crowded market in 
Vladikavkaz. 

</P>
<P>
	OPEC Urges Compliance With Oil Cuts  
</P>
<P>
	VIENNA, Austria (AP) -- OPEC ministers expressed hope today that  
oil-exporting nations would abide by production cuts designed to 
slash total output by more than 2 million barrels a day. The new 
quotas, which are to begin April 1, would remain in effect for a 
full year. Under the deal reached at The Hague, Saudi Arabia, which 
currently produces more than 8 million barrels a day, will take the 
biggest cut -- 585,000 barrels. Formal approval of the production 
cuts is expected in a meeting between leaders Tuesday. 

</P>
<P>
	Michigan St., Duke in Final Four  
</P>
<P>
	ST. LOUIS (AP) -- Top-seeded Michigan State, who twice trailed by  
13 points early in the game, came back to beat No. 3 seed Kentucky 
73-66 today and earn their first trip to the Final Four in 20 
years. The Spartans play Duke next Saturday in the Final Four at 
St. Petersburg, Fla., while Connecticut plays Ohio State in the 
other semifinal. 

</P>
<P>
	McGwire, Sosa Lead Homer Race  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Mark McGwire and Sammy Sosa are making this  
spring seem a lot like last summer. McGwire and Sosa each hit their 
eighth home runs today to remain tied for the spring training lead. 
McGwire's two-run shot came off A.J. Burnett in the third inning of 
the St. Louis Cardinals' 10-4 loss to Florida Marlins split squad. 
Sosa's three-run homer came in the second inning of the Chicago 
Cubs' 10-7 loss to the San Francisco Giants at Mesa, Ariz. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by BRADLEY BROOKS  
</P>
</TEXT>
