<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> US Says Jordan Must Make Changes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	AMMAN, Jordan (AP) -- Jordan stands to benefit from joining the  
World Trade Organization, but it must first introduce copyright and 
other legislation to meet membership requirements, U.S. Ambassador 
William Burns said Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	He told an informal press briefing that if Jordan fails to win  
WTO membership next year, ``the likelihood of the criteria are 
going to get tougher than the ones now employed.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``By becoming a member of the WTO you open up all sorts of  
opportunities'' such as attracting investment, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	But he added, ``WTO membership is not an easy process'' because  
Parliament would need to enact many laws relating to intellectual 
property rights. 
</P>
<P>
	Although Jordan has taken encouraging steps to end piracy,  
``there is still more that needs to be done,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Jordan has introduced several legislative proposals in an effort  
to attract foreign capital that would help ease the burdens of $6.1 
billion foreign debts. But no legislation protecting intellectual 
property has been enacted yet. 
</P>
<P>
	The United States is one of Jordan's largest donors. It has  
contributed tens of millions of dollars on development projects 
here. Its economic and military aid to Jordan in the next three 
years is estimated to be $1 billion. 
</P>
</TEXT>
