<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Weather Postpones Women's Super-G </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HUNTSVILLE, Utah (AP) -- The women's super-G race at the U.S.  
Championships was postponed Sunday after changing weather left the 
hill more fit for sled dogs than alpine racers. 
</P>
<P>
	The course at Snowbasin Ski Resort, which had already suffered  
through a week of unseasonably high temperatures, was hit by rain 
Saturday night and light snow hours before the race. Organizers 
twice pushed back the race's start before postponing it entirely. 
</P>
<P>
	If the weather doesn't improve in the coming days and the race  
is canceled, it will be the third time in the last five years that 
the United States is unable to crown a women's super-G national 
champion. 
</P>
<P>
	The race was also called off because of poor snow at Snowbasin  
in 1995 and last year at Jackson Hole, Wyo. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was an absolutely right decision,'' women's super-G coach  
Jim Tracy said. ``It certainly wasn't canceled due to a lack of 
effort on the part of the course crews and volunteers ... but it's 
always better to be safe than sorry. 
</P>
<P>
	``We can always race another day.''  
</P>
<P>
	That day could be Tuesday, the only open date left on the  
women's schedule. The men's super-G championships are scheduled for 
Snowbasin on Monday, while the women are slated to run the giant 
slalom at Park City Mountain Resort. 
</P>
<P>
	Women's head coach Marjan Cernigoj said there were three  
distinct zones of snow conditions on the mountain after the 
unpredictable weather. New snow was at the top of the run, but 
conditions deteriorated down the length of the course until 
reaching the warm and slushy snow at the bottom. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was terrible all the way down,'' said skier Katie Monahan,  
who won an FIS downhill race on the course on Saturday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
