<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Lady Vols Playing Mind Games </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	GREENSBORO, N.C. (AP) -- For Tennessee coach Pat Summitt, it's  
March Mindset. 
</P>
<P>
	This is the time of year her motivational demands take on new  
urgency, with more talk about mental toughness than on Xs and Os. 
</P>
<P>
	Next up for Summitt and the top-seeded Lady Volunteers (31-2) is  
an NCAA East Regional title game against Duke (27-6) on Monday 
night. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have maintained the commitment to going out and being the  
best team in March with more or less talent,'' said Summitt, whose 
program has won three straight NCAA titles and 21 straight 
tournament games. ``You've got to look at your team and look at 
your opposition and think about how you have to influence them. 
</P>
<P>
	``At this time of year it's a lot about being mentally strong  
and disciplined.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Summitt didn't necessarily see that kind of team in December  
when Tennessee beat the Blue Devils 74-60. 
</P>
<P>
	``We go out and play Duke in early December and we're in foul  
trouble,'' Summitt said Sunday. ``Our sophomores are older and 
wiser now and hopefully they won't be sitting with me (Monday 
night) in the first half. 
</P>
<P>
	``They understand that you help by stopping penetration, not by  
fouling people. That's something that takes mental discipline. We 
talk a lot about that, it's attitude, and not to let anything 
throughout the course of the game take us off our course, not to 
panic. It's a 40-minute game and this team has learned that.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The title game will be at Greensboro Coliseum, about one hour  
from the Duke campus. But the Lady Volunteers will have thousands 
more fans than the Blue Devils will. 
</P>
<P>
	``That has become such a part of our program,'' Summitt said of  
the orange-clad fans. ``It really inspires our team. There have 
been a lot of times (the fans) have been our sixth player and 
they'll get this team going.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Lady Vols have advanced to 11 Final Fours since 1982, while  
the Blue Devils have never gone that far. Duke lost to Arkansas 
last season in the West Regional championship. 
</P>
<P>
	Duke coach Gail Goestenkors welcomes a rematch with Tennessee.  
</P>
<P>
	``Whether we want to admit it or not we were a little  
intimidated going on the floor with them that first game,'' 
Goestenkors said. ``It took us a half to get through that.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Goestenkors thinks a tough early schedule and the demanding play  
of the Atlantic Coast Conference has toughened her team. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're older, we're wiser, we're smarter and we're much  
healthier,'' Goestenkors said. ``We've grown as a team to 
understand our roles a little bit better, who the shooters are, 
when we need to get the ball inside, who is hot and how do we get 
them the ball.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Tennessee All-American Chamique Holdsclaw is closing her career  
with a flourish. The 6-foot-2 forward has scored 23, 39 and 27 
points in her three NCAA tournament games. 
</P>
<P>
	``I just want to go out there and leave everything on the  
court,'' Holdsclaw said. 
</P>
<P>
	She'll be guarded by Duke sophomore Georgia Schweitzer.  
</P>
<P>
	``You just try to keep her from taking over the game,''  
Schweitzer said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
