<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Oscarcast: Long, Dull and Tacky </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Grazie from at least one grateful viewer to  
Roberto Benigni! 
</P>
<P>
	The excitable, ecstatic writer-director-star of ``Life Is  
Beautiful'' was almost the sole salvation of ``The 71st Annual 
Academy Awards.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Could this year's Oscarcast have been any duller? Only if the  
Italian comic superstar hadn't been on hand to accept two Oscars in 
his rapid-fire, euphoric broken English. 
</P>
<P>
	``I want to kiss everybody,'' he said after stepping from  
seat-back to seat-back to reach the stage for his best foreign 
language film trophy. 
</P>
<P>
	A little while later, the Oscarcast got another welcome wakeup  
call when Benigni returned to claim the best actor award: ``I would 
like to be Jupiter and kidnap everybody,'' he bubbled, ``and lie 
down in the firmament making love with everybody!'' 
</P>
<P>
	Who knows what would have gone on had he won a third?  
</P>
<P>
	Otherwise, the broadcast, which ABC aired live from Los Angeles'  
Dorothy Chandler Pavilion Sunday night, was almost unrelievedly 
rated zzzzzzzzzzzzz. And it couldn't all be blamed on the show's 
record-breaking length: 4 hours, 2 minutes. The show was just dull. 
</P>
<P>
	Even the much-awaited climax to the drama surrounding Elia  
Kazan's life achievement award fell flat. 
</P>
<P>
	``More than anybody, he inspired us,'' said Robert De Niro three  
hours into the broadcast. De Niro had joined director Martin 
Scorsese to present the award, an object of bitter debate between 
admirers of the great director and those who denounced him for 
naming colleagues in a government investigation of communist 
influence on Hollywood. 
</P>
<P>
	Viewers saw that Warren Beatty and Meryl Streep were among those  
who stood and applauded. Nick Nolte and Ed Harris were among those 
who sat in stony silence. 
</P>
<P>
	``Thank you all very much,'' said the 89-year-old Kazan. ``I  
think I can just slip away.'' 
</P>
<P>
	And that was that.  
</P>
<P>
	In her third turn as host, Whoopi Goldberg had little new to  
offer the broadcast. Hers was the same tacky, self-satisfied 
performance. 
</P>
<P>
	Her appearances in various Oscar-related costumes, beginning  
with the finery of Queen Elizabeth (not to mention in white-face), 
should have been funny. But Goldberg has a fixation on rude double 
entendres and bodily functions that coarsens everything. 
</P>
<P>
	Observing that William Shakespeare has had a good year in the  
movies, Goldberg purred suggestively, ``Little Willie is very 
large.'' Then there were her quips about ``leaks,'' horse manure, 
and -- well, even if you weren't watching, you're surely familiar 
with grade-school-level risqueness. 
</P>
<P>
	After one of these wisecracks, she made a cackling reference to  
frequent Oscarcast host Billy Crystal: ``You're missin' Billy just 
about now, aincha?'' 
</P>
<P>
	If you only knew, Whoopi.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
