<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-21 11:21:20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Mourning Loses Cool and Game </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MIAMI (AP) -- It took only a few seconds to undo a half-season's  
worth of goodwill by Alonzo Mourning. 
</P>
<P>
	The Miami Heat center, known for allowing his intense demeanor  
to boil over, had earned praise through the first seven weeks of 
the NBA season for being able to meet hard fouls and bad calls with 
a shrug -- even a smile. 
</P>
<P>
	Then Saturday night, the old Mourning resurfaced in the first  
half of Miami's 94-89 loss to Indiana. 
</P>
<P>
	``I heard him say earlier in the year that he'd learned how to  
control himself in those situations,'' Pacers center-forward 
Antonio Davis said. ``I guess now it's back to the drawing board.'' 
</P>
<P>
	With the Heat trailing 31-27 and 5:11 left before halftime,  
Mourning was called for an offensive foul as teammate P.J. Brown 
was attempting a shot in the lane. It appeared Davis would be 
called for bumping Brown, but referee Ted Bernhardt ruled Mourning 
had pushed Davis into the shooter. 
</P>
<P>
	Mourning, incredulous, flung his arms in frustration and yanked  
the gum out of his mouth to speak to Bernhardt. But he turned with 
such force that the first technical came quickly. 
</P>
<P>
	The new Mourning would have grimaced -- maybe even smiled -- and  
turned away. But something kept him from doing so. 
</P>
<P>
	``He kept walking away from me,'' Mourning said. ``I just wanted  
to talk to him. That was my third foul and I need to be on the 
floor in a situation like that. The next time I'm in the game, I 
don't want to pick up a quick fourth. We need to address this now 
before he makes another call like that.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Things actually seemed rather benign as he walked alongside  
Bernhardt, occasionally pumping his arms to punctuate his point. 
Then suddenly, the referee turned, angrily jabbed his finger into 
Mourning's chest and called the second technical. 
</P>
<P>
	``Ted was looking at him the whole time and probably didn't like  
his body language,'' said Heat guard Terry Porter, who was the 
first to reach Mourning. He and Dan Majerle managed to steer their 
centerpiece away from Bernhardt. 
</P>
<P>
	``I didn't want him to do something stupid and miss the Utah  
game,'' Porter said. Miami next plays the Western Conference leader 
Tuesday night at Salt Lake City. 
</P>
<P>
	The scene brought to mind the end of Game 4 in last year's  
first-round playoff series against New York. With victory in hand 
for the Knicks, Mourning inexplicably began flailing away at Larry 
Johnson with 1.4 seconds left. 
</P>
<P>
	Mourning said afterward that the Knicks pushed him over the edge  
by taking cheap shots at the left cheek he had broken earlier in 
the season. Still, it earned him a suspension for Game 5 -- and an 
early exit for the Heat. 
</P>
<P>
	Heat coach Pat Riley could be seen after that incident telling  
Mourning he'd just blown Miami's playoff chances. There was only 
one word for Mourning upon Saturday night's ejection -- Riley merely 
pointed in the direction of the locker room and said, ``Go.''. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was a terrible call,'' Riley said afterward. ``You can get  
a `T,' but you can't push it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	It's too early to tell, but Mourning's outburst could affect the  
Heat's playoff standing. Though Miami remains one game ahead of 
Indiana in the Eastern Conference race, the Pacers now own the 
tiebreaker advantage with two wins in three meetings. They face 
each other one more time, April 18 at Miami. 
</P>
<P>
	``There were two mistakes made, one on his part and one on my  
part,'' Mourning said. ``They're (referees) human, just like I'm 
human. You just live and learn in a situation like that.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Again.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
