<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Navy Servicemen Arrested in Japan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- Three U.S. Navy servicemen were arrested Sunday on  
suspicion of assaulting and robbing a taxi driver in downtown 
Tokyo, police said. 
</P>
<P>
	Police official Yasuhide Iki said the three are based at a U.S.  
naval base in Yokosuka, 30 miles southwest of Tokyo, which is the 
headquarters of the U.S. 7th Fleet. 
</P>
<P>
	Iki identified one of the suspects as Reed Jarrid Duarte, 22,  
but his hometown was not available. Iki declined to identify the 
other two because they were both 19 years old, and according to 
Japanese law, police must withhold the names of suspects who are 
under 20. 
</P>
<P>
	Iki said the three denied attacking the driver.  
</P>
<P>
	He quoted driver Koji Miura, 49, as telling police that he tried  
to give the three $25 change for their fare Saturday as they got 
off at Roppongi, a popular nightclub district in downtown Tokyo. 
One of the servicemen then allegedly punched him in the face and 
robbed him of another $25. 
</P>
<P>
	The three allegedly ran away, but police discovered them in  
streets nearby and arrested them, Iki said. Miura suffered a minor 
injury to his lip, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	U.S. military officials were not immediately available for  
comment. 
</P>
</TEXT>
