<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Unser, Hattori Injured at Miami GP </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HOMESTEAD, Fla. (AP) -- Al Unser Jr. and rookie Naoki Hattori  
broke their legs Sunday when they crashed into each other during 
the first lap of CART's season-opening Marlboro Grand Prix of 
Miami. 
</P>
<P>
	Unser, the former CART series champion, broke his right ankle  
and Hattori suffered a compound fracture of his left leg when they 
hit the wall between the first and second turns at Homestead-Miami 
Speedway. Both drivers were airlifted to a Miami hospital and 
require surgery. 
</P>
<P>
	Unser, second on the all-time CART list with 31 race wins, also  
suffered ligament damage to his left knee. He was to be transferred 
Sunday night to Methodist Hospital in Indianapolis and will undergo 
surgery Monday by Dr. Terry Trammell. 
</P>
<P>
	Hattori, a 32-year-old rookie from Japan, was scheduled for  
surgery Sunday night by Dr. James Hutson at Jackson Memorial 
Hospital in Miami. 
</P>
<P>
	The accident took place seconds after the green flag as Unser  
apparently got pinched by Hattori's intended high line. The 
resulting contact sent both into the wall, bringing out a caution 
flag that lasted 17 laps. 
</P>
<P>
	Dr. Steve Olvey, CART's director of medical services, said both  
drivers were awake and alert immediately after the accident. 
</P>
<P>
	The crash was another blow for Unser, who was trying to end a  
three-year winless streak while coping with the sudden paralysis of 
his 12-year-old daughter Cody. 
</P>
<P>
	Unser was called away from testing at Homestead last month when  
Cody was diagnosed with a virus that attacks the spinal cord. She 
left a basketball game complaining of numbness in her legs. She is 
paralyzed from the waist down and learning to walk again at a 
Phoenix neurological hospital. 
</P>
<P>
	``When it rains, it pours,'' said Michael Andretti, Unser's  
longtime rival who finished second Sunday. ``I feel bad about Cody, 
and now this happens. It's been a tough winter for him. But they're 
tough people. They'll get through it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	It also was a bad start to the scaled-back effort of Marlboro  
Team Penske. After just three wins in the past three seasons, owner 
Roger Penske decided to field a one-car entry for the first time 
since 1970, with Unser as his driver. 
</P>
</TEXT>
