<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 9 a.m. EST  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Balloonists End World Trip  
</P>
<P>
	MUT, Egypt (AP) -- Less than a day after conquering one of the  
great challenges in aviation, the two men who became the first to 
circle the world nonstop in a hot-air balloon landed safely today 
outside of the Western Desert oasis town of Mut. Bertrand Piccard 
and Brian Jones chose to continue their flight past the finish line 
in the hope of landing near the pyramids, but unfavorable winds 
kept them south of their goal. And then they waited -- for nearly 
eight hours -- atop the steep plateau. Two Egyptian army helicopters 
finally picked up the men. 

</P>
<P>
	Serbs Ignore NATO Threats, Attack Rebels  
</P>
<P>
	PRISTINA, Yugoslavia (AP) -- Ignoring NATO threats, Yugoslav  
forces pounded rebel positions in central Kosovo for a second 
straight day today, setting houses ablaze as terrified ethnic 
Albanian civilians fled into the snowy hills. Journalists reported 
seeing smoke rising from villages near the town of Srbrica. Earlier 
the Serbian Media Center reported Kosovo Liberation Army rebels 
fired on a police vehicle near the town, with no casualties. The 
rebel Kosova Press Agency claims up to 15,000 civilians were on the 
run, following an offensive launched as international monitors left 
the country yesterday. 

</P>
<P>
	Israeli Court Rejects Extradition  
</P>
<P>
	JERUSALEM (AP) -- An Israeli Supreme Court justice rejected a  
request today to hear an appeal of a decision not to extradite an 
18-year-old Maryland youth to the United States to face a murder 
charge. In a decision that raised U.S.-Israel tensions, Israel's 
Supreme Court last month ruled that Samuel Sheinbein, who was born 
and raised in the United States, was an Israeli citizen and could 
not be extradited. Sheinbein fled to Israel three days after the 
burned and mutilated corpse of Alfredo Enrique Tello Jr., 19, was 
found in Montgomery County, Md., in September of 1997. A prosecutor 
will issue charges against Sheinbein tomorrow in Tel Aviv district 
court and his trial on the death will be held in Israel. 

</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Clinton's Plane Has Troubles  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- First lady Hillary Rodham Clinton and daughter  
Chelsea's 12-day trip to North Africa got off to a rocky start 
yesterday, including an engine fire. The planned departure from 
Andrews Air Force Base in suburban Maryland was delayed an hour 
because the Air Force Boeing 707 jetliner carrying the president's 
wife and daughter, staff aides and journalists was found to be 
overweight with cargo and luggage. Then as the plane raced down the 
runway for takeoff, flames shot out the rear of the outboard engine 
of the left wing. The plane took off about two hours after its 
originally scheduled departure time. 

</P>
<P>
	Prostitution Ring Preyed on Young  
</P>
<P>
	DETROIT (AP) -- Authorities say they have crushed a prostitution  
ring whose ringleader allegedly lured young, troubled girls to the 
city with promises of sympathy, money and dancing jobs. James 
Coleman, 39, has been arraigned on charges of transporting minors 
across state lines for prostitution and sex. Girls told 
investigators they left troubled homes after Coleman promised them 
money and jobs in Detroit. Once there, promises were replaced with 
10- to 12-hour shifts as prostitutes in motels or as call girls in 
the Detroit area, according to the affidavit. Coleman employed as 
many as 20 girls at a time, investigators say. 

</P>
<P>
	Oscars To Be Awarded Tonight  
</P>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- 'Saving Private Ryan' and 'Shakespeare in  
Love' will battle it out at the Oscars tonight. Shakespeare has 13 
nominations, two more than Ryan. Both are up for best picture, 
along with 'The Thin Red Line,' 'Life is Beautiful' and 
'Elizabeth.' Tom Hanks and Meryl Streep will be trying for their 
third Oscars. Hanks is up for best actor for 'Saving Private Ryan,' 
while Streep is nominated for best actress for 'One True Thing.' 
Roberto Benigni is up for three awards, for acting, directing and 
writing for 'Life is Beautiful.' 

</P>
<P>
	Senators Beat Blues 3-2  
</P>
<P>
	ST. LOUIS (AP) -- Shawn McEachern scored his 30th goal on the  
Ottawa Senators' only shot of the third period for a 3-2 victory 
over the St. Louis Blues last night. The Senators were on the wrong 
end of a 10-0 count when McEachern beat Grant Fuhr on an odd-man 
rush from the right circle at 11:45. The final third-period count 
was 11-1 for the Blues, who had a 22-15 advantage overall. 

</P>
<P>
	Agassi, Becker Lose at Lipton  
</P>
<P>
	KEY BISCAYNE, Fla. (AP) -- Andre Agassi is out at the Lipton  
Championships, and he says he's done with Davis Cup. Hampered by an 
inconsistent serve and sore hamstring, Agassi lost his opening 
match yesterday to fist-pumping Slovakian Dominik Hrbaty, 1-6, 6-3, 
6-2. Agassi, ranked ninth, has yet to reach a final or beat a 
top-20 player this year, so the loss wasn't as big a surprise as 
what came next: His pledge to quit Davis Cup. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by DAVID GOODMAN  
</P>
