<HEADLINE> Coburn Wins Oscar for 'Affliction' </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- James Coburn's performance in ``Affliction''  
as a cop's abusive father contrasts with the more glamorous tough 
guys he played in movies such as ``The Great Escape'' and ``The 
Magnificent Seven.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Coburn, who won the award as best supporting actor Sunday night,  
had made more than 80 movies but had never been nominated for an 
Oscar. 
</P>
<P>
	``Affliction,'' based on the acclaimed novel by Russell Banks,  
deals with depression and drunkenness and the relationships between 
a self-destructive lawman and his family in a small New England 
town. 
</P>
<P>
	He played Glen Whitehouse, the abusive father to the character  
played by Nick Nolte, who was nominated for best actor. 
</P>
<P>
                            	 *------	 
</P>
<P>
	--From the podium: ``I've been working and doing this work for,  
like, over half my life and I finally got one right I guess,'' the 
bearded, silver-haired Coburn growled with a grin. 
</P>
<P>
	--Some previous films: ``Our Man Flint,'' ``In Like Flint,''  
``The Magnificent Seven,'' ``The Great Escape,'' ``The Muppet 
Movie,'' ``Young Guns,'' ``Hudson Hawk,'' ``Maverick.'' 
</P>
<P>
	--Breaking in: The son of an auto mechanic came to Hollywood and  
studied acting as Los Angeles City College and the University of 
Southern California before landing a gunslinger role in the 1959 
movie ``Ride Lonesome.'' 
</P>
<P>
	--Breakthrough role: The 1966 spy spoof ``Our Man Flint.''  
</P>
<P>
	--Bio: Age 70, born in Laurel, Neb.  
</P>
</TEXT>
