<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Middle-Aged Hurt by Taiwan Woes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TAIPEI, Taiwan (AP) -- Taiwan's faltering economy is producing  
the greatest hardships for those least equipped to deal with new 
economic realities -- the middle-aged, less educated, and less 
skilled, an opposition politician said Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	Almost half of respondents to a recent survey said their incomes  
shrunk in 1998 compared to 1997, and about 43 percent said they 
feared losing their jobs, said Chou Ya-shu, a member of the 
Legislature from the Democratic Progressive Party. 
</P>
<P>
	Those more than 40 years old with only an elementary or middle  
school education suffered the deepest cuts in their incomes, and 
were least able to find economic alternatives, Chou said. 
</P>
<P>
	The survey, commissioned by a think tank connected to the main  
opposition party, sampled 1,071 adults on Feb. 23-26. It did not 
provide a sample of error. 
</P>
<P>
	Taiwan's relatively strong economy has shielded it from the  
devastating rises in unemployment and poverty suffered by neighbors 
such as South Korea and Thailand that have been hit worst by the 
Asian economic downturn. But a series of high-profile business 
failures have staggered confidence, and retailers are beginning to 
complain of reduced consumer buying power. 
</P>
<P>
	The biggest fall in exports in 43 years caused economic growth  
to slow to 4.83 percent last year, down from the 1997 rate of 6.8 
percent, Exports plunged 9.4 percent last year. 
</P>
<P>
	Growth is expected to slow still more this year, with the  
government predicting a rate of 4.74 percent, the lowest since 
Taiwan was hit by an oil crisis in 1982. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990321.0033 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-21 05:21:04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  D.C. United 5, Mutiny 2 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TAMPA, Fla. (AP) -- Roy Lassiter had two goals and Carlos Llamosa  
and Jaime Moreno scored four minutes apart early in the second half 
as D.C. United beat Tampa Bay 5-2 in a Major League Soccer opener 
Saturday night. 
</P>
<P>
	Lassiter, traded from Tampa Bay to D.C. United last season, made  
it 3-0 in the 66th minute and added his second goal in the 86th 
minute. He has 20 goals in 26 games with United. 
</P>
<P>
	``I had a real good feeling before the game,'' D.C. United coach  
Thomas Rongen said. ``The core of our players have been together 
and they were ready to play. There was a lot of emotion in he 
lockeroom.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Llamosa's header following a corner kick by Marco Etcheverry in  
the 50th minute made it 1-0 and Moreno made it 2-0 in the 54th 
minute from point-blank range after Ben Olsen's feed. 
</P>
<P>
	Jefferson Gottardi scored Tampa Bay's goals in the 67th and 88th  
minutes. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm disappointed and angry because from my standpoint for what  
I feel our team was capable of, we didn't play,'' Mutiny coach Tim 
Hankinson said. ``On the most exciting day of the year, our guys 
did not give us their fight.'' 
</P>
