<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Pineaff Wins Tampa Bay Derby </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	OLDSMAR, Fla. (AP) -- Pineaff rallied from more than 13 lengths  
back at the half-mile pole to edge fellow Kentucky Derby contender 
Menifee in the $150,000 Tampa Bay Derby on Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	Menifee, a 2-5 favorite, lost for the first time in four career  
starts and prevented Pat Day from becoming the first jockey to ride 
two winners in the 19-year history of the event. 
</P>
<P>
	Day rode Parade Ground to victory in the 1998 Tampa Bay Derby.  
</P>
<P>
	``We didn't expect to get beat today, but we didn't expect to be  
undefeated our whole life either,'' said Elliott Walden, Menifee's 
trainer. 
</P>
<P>
	``I thought he ran a credible race. If he had gotten beat by  
five lengths and stopped in the lane, I would have been really 
disappointed.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Pineaff, ridden by Jose Santos, completed the mile and one-  
sixteenth at Tampa Bay Downs in 1:45.33 on a track made dull by 
morning rain. 
</P>
<P>
	The Kentucky-bred colt, a 6-1 shot in the six-horse field, paid  
$14, $3.60 and $2.10 after edging Menifee by a length and Doneraile 
Court by five. 
</P>
<P>
	``When our horse acted up in the paddock, I knew he would win,''  
Pineaff's owner Roy Monroe said. ``I was surprised. He never did 
this before.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Despite the loss, Day was satisfied with his bay colt's first  
effort at this distance. 
</P>
<P>
	``My opinion of this horse hasn't diminished,'' Day said. ``It's  
the first time he was really tested, the first time around two 
turns on a tiring race track.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Day floated wide around both turns, then rallied to take a brief  
lead down the stretch. Pineaff moved from the inside on the second 
turn, then followed Menifee to the outside for the winning charge 
in the final sixteenth. 
</P>
<P>
	Both Pineaff and Menifee are expected to run in the Blue Grass  
Stakes at Keeneland on April 10. 
</P>
</TEXT>
