<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Steve Alford Eyes Iowa Job </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SPRINGFIELD, Mo. (AP) -- Southwest Missouri State basketball  
coach Steve Alford says he has been interviewed by Iowa and is 
interested in coaching the Hawkeyes next season. 
</P>
<P>
	Iowa athletic director Bob Bowlsby said last April that coach  
Tom Davis' contract would not be extended past this season, his 
13th at Iowa. 
</P>
<P>
	Both Davis and Alford coached their teams to two victories in  
the NCAA tournament before dropping regional semifinal contests. 
</P>
<P>
	Alford told reporters he is ``99 percent'' sure he will coach at  
Iowa or Southwest Missouri State next year. 
</P>
<P>
	Alford said he has not officially been offered the Iowa job, but  
said he has several questions and plans to speak again soon with 
Bowlsby. 
</P>
<P>
	``Within the next 72 hours, there have to be a lot of decisions  
made,'' said Alford, whose Bears lost 78-61 Friday to top-ranked 
Duke while Iowa was eliminated from the tourney the night before 
with a 78-68 loss to Connecticut. 
</P>
<P>
	``I wish the timing was such that a decision wouldn't have to be  
made right away because there's not a lot of time to cherish what 
happened with this team,'' said the 34-year-old Alford, who has a 
78-48 record in four years at Southwest Missouri State. 
</P>
<P>
	About 300 people greeted the team's charter flight on its  
arrival at Springfield-Branson Regional Airport on Saturday night. 
One fan carried a sign that said, ``Steve Must Stay.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Alford, a collegiate standout at Indiana, called Iowa ``one of  
only four or five programs in the country I would consider leaving 
SMS for.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He said the financial package at Iowa would double his current  
income at Southwest Missouri State, which has been estimated at 
about $200,000. 
</P>
<P>
	``Business is only one part of it,'' Alford said. ``Whatever  
happens has to be right for me personally and right for my 
family.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Alford said he has not told his team whether he intends to stay  
or leave for Iowa. 
</P>
<P>
	Southwest Missouri State president John Keiser said Friday the  
school was ``glad to have had him and we hope we can keep him.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``But if not, we thank him for giving us a program that will be  
attractive enough to get another good coach,'' Keiser said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
