<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Kenyan Wins Rome Marathon </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ROME (AP) -- Philip Tanui was supposed to set the pace Sunday and  
help fellow Kenyan Philip Chirchir win the Rome Marathon. But Tanui 
discarded that plan and pulled away to win his first title over the 
26-mile, 385-yard distance. 
</P>
<P>
	Tanui, who trains with Chirchir in Brescia, Italy, helped  
Chirchir until there were about 5 miles left, then broke away. He 
crossed the finish line alone in the shade of the Colosseum. 
</P>
<P>
	Tanui's time was 2 hours, 9 minutes, 56 seconds.  
</P>
<P>
	Dmitri Kapitanov of Russia surged into second place down the  
stretch and finished at 2:10:10. Chirchir was third, another five 
seconds back. 
</P>
<P>
	Italy's Maura Viceconte, third at last year's European  
championships, was the women's winner, at 2:29:36. She took the 
lead at about the halfway mark and was never challenged. 
</P>
<P>
	Jane Salumae of Estonia was second at 2:30:40.  
</P>
<P>
	The 5,000 entrants wound through the streets and squares of the  
city, including past the Spanish Steps, Piazza Navona and the 
Circus Maximus in the historic center. 
</P>
<P>
	Mayor Franceso Rutelli, who participated in the race's 3.1-mile  
event Sunday, said the next Rome Marathon will be run Jan. 1, 2000, 
with the course starting and finishing at St. Peter's Square. 
</P>
</TEXT>
