<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Single Empire Wins San Luis Rey </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ARCADIA, Calif. (AP) -- Single Empire went four-wide into the  
stretch and staved off Kessem Power by a nose to win Sunday's 
$250,000 San Luis Rey Stakes at Santa Anita. 
</P>
<P>
	Kent Desormeaux, riding his third winner on the card, guided  
Single Empire over 1 1/2 miles on the turf in 2:27 4-5. The Irish-bred 
winner paid $11.20, $5.40 and $4.20 in his second start in the 
United States. 
</P>
<P>
	``Boy, when my horse got his legs underneath him and set sail  
for the target, he put on a kick like the race was only 
three-quarters of a mile. It was close, but I knew we had won,'' 
Desormeaux said. 
</P>
<P>
	New Zealand-bred Kessem Power, who won the San Luis Rey last  
year, returned $4.40 and $2.80, while Brazilian-bred Alvo Certo was 
another 1 3-4 lengths back in third and paid $4 to show. 
</P>
<P>
	``I probably would have done better if I got a little traffic,  
and, when I needed it most, I didn't get it,'' said Michael Kinane, 
Kessem Power's jockey. ``But when I went for the run, I had to take 
it. Otherwise, it was going to close down. He really quickened, but 
you could see he went to idling a little bit.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The victory, worth $150,000, increased Single Empire's career  
earnings to $554,113, with four wins in 10 starts. 
</P>
</TEXT>
