<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-21 20:52:22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Academy Honors Filmmaker Jewison </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Norman Jewison's 36-year producing and  
directing career brought him the Irving G. Thalberg Memorial Award, 
bestowed by the Academy for exemplary moviemaking. 
</P>
<P>
	His films have earned 41 nominations and 12 Academy Awards,  
including Best Picture for 1967's ``In the Heat of the Night.'' His 
four other bids in that category: ``The Russians Are Coming, the 
Russians Are Coming'' (1966), ``Fiddler on the Roof'' (1971), ``A 
Soldier's Story'' (1984) and ``Moonstruck,'' (1987). 
</P>
<P>
	He danced onstage Sunday to the strains of ``If I Were A Rich  
Man,'' from ``Fiddler'' and accepted his lifetime achievement award 
from presenter Nicolas Cage. 
</P>
<P>
	He thanked everyone he had ever worked with, and praised the art  
of brevity. 
</P>
<P>
	His parting advice to young filmmakers: ``Just find some good  
stories. Never mind the gross, the top 10, the bottom 10, what's 
the rating, what's the demographic,'' he said to loud applause. 
</P>
<P>
	``So just tell a story that moves us to laughter and tears, and  
perhaps reveals a little truth about ourselves.'' 
</P>
<P>
	His movies were marked by struggle and nonconformity -- ``In the  
Heat of the Night, when Sidney Poitier's inner-city detective 
fights Southern racism, to ``Moonstruck,'' when Cher defies family 
convention for a younger man. 
</P>
<P>
	Born in Toronto, Jewison's entertainment career began in London  
as an actor and writer for the BBC. In the 1950s, he returned home 
to direct television shows, eventually moving to New York, where he 
directed musical-variety shows for the Canadian Broadcasting Co. 
featuring Judy Garland, Frank Sinatra and Harry Belafonte. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1963, he directed his first film, ``Forty Pounds of  
Trouble,'' a comedy starring Tony Curtis and Suzanne Pleshette. In 
1965, ``The Cincinnati Kid,'' starring a young Steve McQueen, 
established Jewison's entry into serious filmmaking. 
</P>
<P>
	Jewison also served as producer and director on ``The Thomas  
Crown Affair'' (1968), ``Jesus Christ Superstar (1973), ``Agnes of 
God'' (1985), and ``In Country'' (1989). 
</P>
</TEXT>
