<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Soccer Head May Seek Bribe Probe </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) -- Lennart Johansson, president of European soccer's  
governing body, is reported to have asked for an investigation into 
a claim that 20 officials were bribed to ensure that Sepp Blatter 
beat him in last year's election for FIFA president. 
</P>
<P>
	The bribes, amounting to a million dollars, came from the leader  
of a Middle Eastern state, according to the Observer. 
</P>
<P>
	The claim is made ``How They Stole the Game,'' a book by British  
author David Yallop. FIFA, soccer's international governing body, 
obtained an injunction last fall blocking the sale of the book in 
Switzerland. 
</P>
<P>
	A Dutch court last week refused to grant a similar injunction  
preventing publication in the Netherlands. 
</P>
<P>
	Johansson asked FIFA to look into the claim made in the book,  
according to the Observer. 
</P>
<P>
	Johansson, who was a strong favorite to win the FIFA election  
until Blatter entered the contest, was dismayed that 20 FIFA 
members, notably from African countries, changed their allegiances 
in the last few weeks before the election in June. 
</P>
<P>
	The book said $1 million in cash was flown by the Middle Eastern  
figure, who was not identified, to the Meridien Hotel in Paris and 
given to the 20 FIFA delegates before the election. 
</P>
<P>
	Reacting to the fact that Blatter was objecting to the book's  
publication, Johansson reportedly said: ``I have reasons to ask 
myself 'why should (FIFA) be against it?' I think that Blatter 
should have an inquiry.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Blatter was quoted as saying there was no need for an  
investigation. 
</P>
<P>
	``I cannot open an inquiry into myself. The elections are now  
finished,'' he told the newspaper 
</P>
</TEXT>
