<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Iowa Wins Wrestling Title, Again </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	STATE COLLEGE, Pa. (AP) -- Once again, it's Iowa.  
</P>
<P>
	The Hawkeyes -- who looked vulnerable after losing four dual  
meets and their first Big Ten Tournament in a quarter-century -- won 
the NCAA Division I wrestling championships Saturday, 100 1/2-98 1/2 over 
Minnesota in the first tournament to be decided by the final match 
in more than two decades. 
</P>
<P>
	Iowa's second-year coach Jim Zalesky called this title more  
satisfying than last year's. 
</P>
<P>
	``With this group, it's sweeter because nobody expected it,'' he  
said. ``Last year, we had the horses to win it, everyone knew we 
had the horses. We had guys who'd been here. This year, we only had 
one guy who'd been here.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Iowa's fifth straight national title -- its eighth in the past  
nine years -- came down to the heavyweight final, the most 
anticipated showdown of the week. 
</P>
<P>
	Stephen Neal, Cal State-Bakersfield's heavyweight and the  
defending champion, won his 83rd straight match 3-2 against 
Minnesota's Brock Lesnar to the cheers of the Hawkeyes faithful. 
</P>
<P>
	``I waited for him to make a mistake,'' Neal said. ``He made one  
and I made none.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm amazed,'' Lesnar said afterward. ``I just -- I gave all I  
had and I'm just really disappointed. I wrestled 110 percent and I 
wouldn't ask more of myself.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Golden Gophers -- who have never won a national title, but  
beat the Hawkeyes in the Big Ten Tournament this month -- started 
the finals two points ahead of Iowa. 
</P>
<P>
	But the Hawkeyes had two finalists win: Doug Schwab at 141, beat  
Michael Lightner of Oklahoma 4-2 on a takedown with 18 seconds 
left; and T.J. Williams at 149, improved to 40-0 with a 5-3 win 
against Mount Carmel (Ill.) High School teammate Tony Davis of 
Northern Iowa. 
</P>
<P>
	``When you're in the national finals, that's enough in itself,''  
Schwab said. ``The team title, putting us back in the lead, that's 
extra incentive.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Zalesky said his team peaked at the right time.  
</P>
<P>
	``I had some concerns in the middle part of the season,'' he  
said. ``That's why I didn't try to get them emotionally high until 
the last two weeks.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Those early victories by Schwab and Williams turned the tide for  
Iowa and put pressure on Minnesota's three finalists. Only one 
Gopher won a final. 
</P>
<P>
	``Couple of our guys didn't wrestle up to their seeds and Iowa's  
did,'' said Minnesota coach J Robinson. He had thought the Gophers 
could win it with Lesnar. 
</P>
<P>
	``Neal took one shot. That's how close it was,'' he said.  
</P>
<P>
	To set up the tournament-deciding heavyweight match, Minnesota's  
Tim Hartung at 197, the 1998 champion, pulled out a dramatic 2-1 
victory against 1997 champ Lee Fullhart. Hartung finished his 
season 39-0 and won the last 55 matches of his career. 
</P>
<P>
	Hartung took Fullhart down with 34 seconds left to finish his  
career 9-1 against the Iowa wrestler. Fullhart nearly reversed 
Hartung in the final minute. 
</P>
<P>
	Minnesota's Brandon Eggum was the second of Minnesota's three  
finalists to lose, 6-1 to Iowa State's Cael Sanderson (39-0). 
Sanderson, a redshirt freshman, was named the tournament's most 
outstanding wrestler. 
</P>
<P>
	Oklahoma State -- No. 1 coming into the nationals with two  
defending champs, another No. 1 seed and a No. 2 seed -- finished 
third with 84 points. 
</P>
<P>
	The Cowboys sent only one wrestler into the finals, Eric  
Guerrero, who won his third national title at 133 by taking down 
Iowa State's Cody Sanderson 55 seconds into overtime for a 3-1 
victory. He is the 13th three-time champion at Oklahoma State. 
</P>
<P>
	``To accomplish a little of what they've accomplished in their  
lives, it's an unbelievable feeling. It probably won't hit me until 
I'm 60 years old,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Of Penn State's three finalists, only Glenn Pritzlaff at 174  
won, 10-4 against Otto Olson of Michigan. Unbeaten Jeremy Hunter at 
125 lost 7-4 to Stephen Abas of Fresno State. Clint Musser at 157 
lost to Casey Cunningham of Central Michigan, 2-1. Cunningham is 
Central Michigan's first national champion. 
</P>
<P>
	Kirk White, No. 2 at 165, became Boise State's first national  
champion by beating Rodney Jones of Oklahoma 3-1 despite suffering 
a pinched neck nerve and numbness during parts of the last two 
matches. 
</P>
<P>
	Teammate Larry Quisel placed third at 157 after being upset in  
his first match, which included a controversial timekeeping call. 
He had to win eight straight matches, including five seeded 
wrestlers. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's a great accomplishment to be the first one. I'm not going  
to be the last one,'' White said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
