<DOCNO> APW19990321.0049 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-21 11:32:09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Elfman Avoids Trappings of Stardom </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- With a hit sitcom and a new movie coming out,  
``Dharma &AMP; Greg'' star Jenna Elfman has a few tips for staying sane 
in Hollywood. 
</P>
<P>
	``Do other things,'' Elfman says in the March 18-25 issue of  
Time Out New York magazine. ``I don't just act. It starts to feel 
like you're digging into an open wound when you do the same thing 
all the time. It becomes achy, sore and tiresome.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Although she co-stars in the upcoming film ``Ed TV,'' Elfman  
feels typecast by her perky character on ``Dharma &AMP; Greg.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``I want people to start offering me some big dramatic parts,''  
she said. ``Sometimes people get locked in this spunky girl thing, 
like I do every week. I want the opportunity to do other things, 
too.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Elfman, 27, got her start in show business as a dancer,  
appearing on the 1991 Academy Awards show and with the rock group 
ZZ Top on a 1994 concert tour as a ``Legs Girl'' dancing to the 
song ``She's Got Legs.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Past credits include appearances on ``Roseanne,'' ``NYPD Blue,''  
``Townies'' and the films ``Grosse Pointe Blank'' and 
``Krippendorf's Tribe.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
