<HEADLINE> 4 Large Italy Banks Talk Mergers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ROME (AP) -- San Paolo and Unicredito Italiano -- Italy's largest  
and third-largest banks, respectively -- each proposed mergers 
Sunday that would reshape the top tier of the country's banking 
system. 
</P>
<P>
	Unicredito Italiano said it would propose a merger to Banca  
Commerciale Italiana. If BCI accepted, the deal would create 
Italy's largest bank, with assets of about $286 billion. 
</P>
<P>
	Unicredito said it would offer eight ordinary shares for every  
five of BCI's. Unicredito's board authorized the offer after 
``doing everything to assure that it was a friendly offer,'' the 
bank said. 
</P>
<P>
	There was no immediate response from BCI.  
</P>
<P>
	Hours after that bid was announced, Italy's current leading  
bank, San Paolo, said it would pursue a merger with Banca di Roma. 
</P>
<P>
	Their merger would produce a bank only slightly smaller than the  
Unicredito-BCI combination. 
</P>
<P>
	BCI is Italy's fourth-largest bank; Banca di Roma is the  
fifth-largest. 
</P>
<P>
	Merger talks among banks throughout Europe have become  
commonplace in anticipation of European monetary union. 
</P>
<P>
	Banca di Roma broke off talks with BCI two weeks ago and allowed  
a Dutch holding company to take a stake, setting off this weekend's 
merger talks. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
