<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Princess Anne Calls for IOC Shakeup </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) -- Princess Anne, who has remained silent during the  
biggest scandal in Olympic history, has written her fellow IOC 
members with suggestions on reforming the games. 
</P>
<P>
	An IOC member since 1988 and a former Olympic equestrian rider,  
the princess says the site of the Summer Games should be rotated 
around the world. 
</P>
<P>
	She also recommends limits on visits by IOC members and  
restrictions on who may serve in the IOC. 
</P>
<P>
	Princess Anne did not attend last week's emergency meeting in  
Switzerland in which the IOC expelled six members for accepting 
cash or other inducements during Salt Lake's successful bid for the 
2002 Winter Games. 
</P>
<P>
	She wrote the other 105 members after reading the report of the  
investigation, and her comments appeared in the Sunday Times. 
</P>
<P>
	``I speak from experience of having been president of  
International Equestrian Federation when I first became a member of 
the IOC, that there are conflicts of interests that can put 
individuals under real pressure,'' she wrote. 
</P>
<P>
	She suggests that in choosing the host for the Summer Games the  
world should be divided into quarters or thirds, with one city in 
each segment making a bid. 
</P>
<P>
	She also thinks heads of international sports federations should  
be banned from sitting on the IOC. That would prevent them from 
visiting bidding cities twice -- once as an IOC member and again as 
representatives of their federations. 
</P>
<P>
	The suggestion concerning federation heads is opposed by IOC  
president Juan Antonio Samaranch. He wants such individuals in the 
IOC but only as long as they lead their federation. 
</P>
<P>
	Referring to the expulsions, which followed the resignations of  
four other members, Princess Anne said it was obvious ``the actions 
of a few have tarnished the movement. 
</P>
<P>
	``We cannot and must not condone such actions and the only  
option of those members of those members who have been compromised 
is to leave the movement,'' she said. 
</P>
<P>
	She urged remaining members to ``live up to our own high  
standards and make sure that in Sydney only the best will do.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
