<HEADLINE> 'Forces' Too Strong for Mob Comedy / Box Office  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- The romantic comedy ``Forces of Nature''  
knocked ``Analyze This'' from the top of the box office in a 
generally lackluster Oscar weekend, according to industry estimates 
Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	The movie, starring Ben Affleck as a straight-laced groom-to-be  
who falls for free-spirited Sandra Bullock on the way to his 
wedding, opened with $13.9 million in ticket sales. 
</P>
<P>
	``Analyze This'' had $11.9 million, dropping to No. 2 in its  
third week. The mobster-in-therapy comedy with Robert De Niro and 
Billy Crystal held the top spot for two weeks. 
</P>
<P>
	As Hollywood prepared for Sunday night's Academy Awards, only  
one Oscar-nominated film made it into the top 10. ``Shakespeare in 
Love,'' up for 13 nominations including best picture, was in ninth 
place with $2.8 million. 
</P>
<P>
	Overall, box office receipts for the week's top 12 films totaled  
$58.1 million, down 25.4 percent over the same period last year, 
according to Exhibitor Relations Co. Inc. 
</P>
<P>
	Final figures were to be released Monday.  
</P>
<P>
	Some analysts suggested theaters gave up a ride on Oscar's gravy  
train by replacing contenders with new releases. 
</P>
<P>
	This time last year, crowds still were swarming to ``Titanic,''  
``Good Will Hunting'' and ``As Good As It Gets,'' said Robert 
Bucksbaum of Reel Source, Inc. 
</P>
<P>
	``A lot of high-profile movies that everyone wanted to see were  
still in the mainstream around Oscar time last year,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	New releases had mixed results.  
</P>
<P>
	``True Crime,'' with Clint Eastwood as a broken-down reporter on  
a crusade to save a condemned man, was No. 3 with $5.3 million. The 
animated version of the musical ``The King and I'' placed sixth 
with $4.1 million. But ``Ravenous,'' a tale of cannibalism in the 
Old West, opened out of the Top 10 with a weak take of $950,000. 
</P>
<P>
	Here are estimated grosses for Friday through Sunday at North  
American theaters: 
</P>
<P>
	1. ``Forces of Nature,'' $13.9 million.  
</P>
<P>
	2. ``Analyze This,'' $11.9 million.  
</P>
<P>
	3. ``True Crime,'' $5.3 million.  
</P>
<P>
	4. ``Baby Geniuses,'' $4.5 million.  
</P>
<P>
	5. ``Cruel Intentions,'' $4.2 million.  
</P>
<P>
	6. ``The King and I,'' $4.1 million.  
</P>
<P>
	7. ``The Rage: Carrie 2,'' $3.6 million.  
</P>
<P>
	8. ``The Corruptor,'' $3 million.  
</P>
<P>
	9. ``Shakespeare in Love,'' $2.8 million.  
</P>
<P>
	10. ``The Deep End of the Ocean,'' $2.7 million.  
</P>
