<HEADLINE> Blue Jays' Fernandez Chases Fan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DUNEDIN, Fla. (AP) -- Toronto Blue Jays infielder Tony Fernandez  
chased after a fan Sunday after he was heckled between morning 
workouts. 
</P>
<P>
	Fernandez, who ran into the stands after the fan, had to be  
restrained by manager Jim Fregosi and pitching coach Mel Queen. 
</P>
<P>
	The confrontation began when the man asked Fernandez for an  
autograph as the player left the field and headed to the Blue Jays' 
covered batting cages. Fernandez said he'd sign after his workout. 
</P>
<P>
	The fan became snide, saying, ``Oh, you're just going to the  
clubhouse.'' 
</P>
<P>
	After several exchanges, with the fan provocatively calling out  
for security, Fernandez dropped his bats and jogged through a gate 
in a chain-link fence separating players from fans. 
</P>
<P>
	Fregosi and Queen, who were chatting nearby, raced over to pull  
Fernandez back on to the field. 
</P>
<P>
	The former Gold Glove shortstop said the same fan bothered him  
Saturday. 
</P>
