<P>
	Gwyneth Paltrow Wins Best Actress  
</P>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Gwyneth Paltrow won the best actress award  
for her role in ``Shakespeare in Love,'' the movie which led all 
contenders with 13 nominations. Earlier, Roberto Benigni won best 
actor for his role in 'Life is Beautiful,' a tragicomedy about a 
father who protects his son from the horrors of the Holocaust, at 
tonight's Academy Awards. The film also got the nod as the best 
foreign film. The Italian wrote, directed and starred in the movie. 

</P>
<P>
	Final Efforts for Kosovo Peace  
</P>
<P>
	LIKOVAC, Yugoslavia (AP) -- Senior envoy Richard Holbrooke is  
expected to meet with Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic within 
hours in a final diplomatic effort at peace in Kosovo. Earlier, a 
top Yugoslav Army general said his troops are ready ``to repel any 
aggression against our country.'' NATO Airstrikes are likely to 
follow if the talks end with Milosevic defiant on two counts: still 
refusing a Kosovo peace plan and persisting in pressing an 
offensive against outgunned Kosovo rebels. 

</P>
<P>
	Iran To Be Sued by Ex-Hostage  
</P>
<P>
	ATHENS, Ohio (AP) -- Terry Anderson, the former Associated Press  
correspondent, is suing Iran for $100 million for the six years he 
was held hostage in Lebanon. The lawsuit accuses Iran of having 
sponsored his captors. But the biggest obstacle to Anderson's 
getting any money may be the U.S. government. The Clinton 
administration has thwarted plaintiffs in similar lawsuits from 
collecting millions of dollars awarded by U.S. courts, even though 
the damage claims are against countries the State Department labels 
as sponsors of terrorism. In October, the president issued a 
blanket waiver of a requirement that federal agencies help obtain 
that money. 

</P>
<P>
	Johnson Press Secretary Reedy Dies  
</P>
<P>
	MILWAUKEE (AP) -- George Reedy, former press secretary for  
President Lyndon Johnson who quit after disagreeing with Johnson's 
Vietnam War policies, died today at 81. Reedy died after a short 
illness at a Milwaukee nursing home where he had been living, an 
employee said. After working for UPI in Washington, D.C., Reedy 
joined the U.S. Senate staff of Johnson, a Texas Democrat, in 1951. 
Reedy stayed with Johnson, only to break away in 1966 over 
disagreements about Johnson's pursuit of the Vietnam War. 

</P>
<P>
	Train Crash Witness Accounts Vary  
</P>
<P>
	BOURBONNAIS, Ill. (AP) -- There may be a conflict in the  
eyewitness accounts of the deadly Amtrak train crash in Illinois. 
``We have not been able to completely reconcile the statements that 
are possibly conflicting,'' said National Transportation Safety 
Board spokesman Jamie Finch. He would not comment on what the 
possible conflicts were. Eleven people were killed and more than 
100 injured in when the Amtrak train crashed into the truck on 
March 15. 

</P>
<P>
	Mine Explodes Near Chechen Leader  
</P>
<P>
	GROZNY, Russia (AP) -- A mine exploded near Chechen President  
Aslan Maskhadov's motorcade today in an assassination attempt while 
he was returning to his residence. Maskhadov was not hurt. One 
person was killed and eight were wounded by the radio-controlled 
device, said the president's press secretary, according to the 
Interfax news agency. It was the second explosion to rock the 
troubled Caucasus region in just three days. At least 51 people 
were killed in an explosion Friday at a crowded market in 
Vladikavkaz. 

</P>
<P>
	Australia Braces for Severe Cyclone  
</P>
<P>
	PERTH, Australia (AP) -- Cyclone Vance, packing winds up to 180  
mph near its core, battered the sparsely populated northwest coast 
of Australia on Monday, forcing the evacuation of most residents. 
Forecasters warned that the cyclone would bring with it a tide 23 
feet higher than normal, very large waves and flooding in the 
region over the next few days. At Onslow, 745 miles north of Perth, 
one woman who decided to stay home and ride out the storm said, 
``It's pretty awesome out there, rain going sideways with the wind, 
trees down, branches everywhere. 

</P>
<P>
	Hornets Beat Bucks 94-87  
</P>
<P>
	MILWAUKEE (AP) -- Eddie Jones scored 23 points and David Wesley  
added 16 Sunday night as the Charlotte Hornets got a 94-87 victory 
over the Milwaukee Bucks. Jones scored seven consecutive points to 
cap a 10-point run to open the fourth quarter as Charlotte went up 
80-70. 

</P>
<P>
	Michigan State, Duke in Final Four  
</P>
<P>
	ST. LOUIS (AP) -- Top-seeded Michigan State, who twice trailed by  
13 points early in the game, came back to beat No. 3 seed Kentucky 
73-66 today and earn their first trip to the Final Four in 20 
years. The Spartans play Duke next Saturday in the Final Four at 
St. Petersburg, Fla., while Connecticut plays Ohio State in the 
other semifinal. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by BRADLEY BROOKS  
</P>
