<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-21 09:21:47 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> NHL Trading Activity Picks Up </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Break up the New York Islanders? Actually, general manager Mike  
Milbury is doing a pretty good job of it all by himself. 
</P>
<P>
	Never shy about making trades, Milbury pulled off three over the  
weekend as the NHL's trading deadline loomed on Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	The Islanders traded goaltender Tommy Salo to Edmonton, center  
Robert Reichel to Phoenix and left wing Ted Donato to Ottawa on a 
busy day Saturday that included a blockbuster, seven-player deal 
between the Oilers and Chicago Blackhawks. 
</P>
<P>
	``The number of teams with a No. 1 goalie is broad,'' Milbury  
said after dealing Salo to Edmonton for center-left wing Mats 
Lindgren and an eighth-round pick in this year's entry draft. ``The 
market for a No. 1 goalie is limited. I bandied a bunch of names 
around and settled on Lindgren.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Salo is making a clean start in Edmonton after an unhappy season  
with the Islanders. Salo was miffed when Milbury acquired goalie 
Felix Potvin from Toronto earlier this season. He debuted Saturday 
night by making 23 saves in a victory over Vancouver, helping the 
Oilers end a six-game winless streak. 
</P>
<P>
	Potvin had a rough start and Salo got more work when Bill  
Stewart replaced Milbury as coach. Potvin has been out recently 
with an injury. 
</P>
<P>
	``He could see it coming,'' Milbury said of trading Salo. ``It  
hasn't worked for him or the team and when it doesn't work, it's 
time to move on. I wish him the best.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Milbury dealt left wing Donato to the Ottawa Senators for a  
fourth-round pick. Then he sent center Robert Reichel and two draft 
picks to the Phoenix Coyotes for left wing Brad Isbister and one of 
Phoenix's picks. 
</P>
<P>
	Regarding the 6-foot-4 Lingren, who had five goals in 48 games  
for the Oilers, Milbury said: 
</P>
<P>
	``He's got some size. He's versatile in that he can play both  
center and left wing. He's good on draws, and we think he can score 
more than he's shown.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Milbury started to change the Islanders dramatically when he  
sent promising young defenseman Bryan Berard to Toronto in the deal 
for Potvin. He started clearing out the veterans on March 9 when he 
traded defenseman Scott Lachance to Montreal for a third-round 
pick. 
</P>
<P>
	Milbury said that Lachance's trade was a salary dump, since he  
felt he wasn't worth tending a qualifying offer at $1.25 million as 
a Group-V free agent. 
</P>
<P>
	Oilers general manager Glen Sather, who promised that changes  
would be made in Edmonton, not only acquired Salo from the 
Islanders but four players in a seven-player swap with Chicago. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's a major shakeup for the team and it is unfortunate to do  
it at this time of the year, but we felt we needed to inject some 
life into the club,'' Sather said. 
</P>
<P>
	The Oilers, battling Calgary for the eighth and final playoff  
spot in the NHL's Western Conference, have won only once in their 
last seven games. 
</P>
<P>
	Sather sent defenseman Boris Mironov, forward Dean McAmmond and  
prospect Jonas Elofsson to the Blackhawks for center Chad Kilger, 
left wings Daniel Cleary and Ethan Moreau and defenseman Christian 
Laflamme. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think we have enough depth up front that we can afford to do  
something like this,'' Blackhawks general manager Bob Murray told 
WMAQ-AM in Chicago. ``We're giving up a lot of young potential in 
this deal and I just felt we were deep enough that the time was now 
to do something with it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In other deals Saturday, the Philadelphia Flyers acquired left  
wing Mikael Andersson and right wing Sandy McCarthy from the Tampa 
Bay Lightning in a trade for left wing Colin Forbes and a 
conditional draft pick. 
</P>
<P>
	The NHL trading deadline is 3 p.m. on Tuesday.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
