<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Latin American Briefs /  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BOGOTA, Colombia (AP) -- Two small planes carrying 15 people were  
reported missing Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	Rescue workers said they have been unable to locate the planes,  
which were carrying a TV crew and government development workers. 
</P>
<P>
	A DC-3 cargo plane carrying eight people vanished Thursday after  
flying out of Cucuta, 390 miles northeast of Bogota near the border 
with Venezuela. 
</P>
<P>
	The other plane, a Piper carrying a two-man TV crew and  
officials from a federal agency working to curb illegal drug crops, 
disappeared Saturday in storm weather near Ataco, 110 miles 
southwest of Bogota in Tolima state. 
</P>
<P>
	Officials have asked leftist guerillas, active in the  
mountainous region, not to fire on search helicopters. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	RIO DE JANEIRO, Brazil (AP) -- Police arrested two police  
officers and three women Sunday in the kidnapping of a Brazilian 
pop duo's brother, hours after the man was released. 
</P>
<P>
	Wellington Camargo, who had part of his ear severed during his  
captivity, was receiving medical treatment but appeared well, his 
family's lawyer Paulo Viana said in TV interview. 
</P>
<P>
	A 28-year-old paraplegic, Camargo was seized on Dec. 16 in  
Goiania, capital of midwestern state Goias, 840 miles northwest of 
Rio. Late Friday, his brothers, country music stars Zeze di Camargo 
and Luciano, paid a $300,000 ransom. 
</P>
<P>
	Soon after his release Sunday, Wellington Camargo was found by a  
motorcyclist 18 miles from Goiania, TV Globo reported. Police later 
arrested three women and two police officers in connection with the 
kidnapping. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	RIO DE JANEIRO, Brazil (AP) -- The government has helped free 777  
people from slave labor since 1995 but hundreds more still work 
against their will in Brazil, a magazine reported Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	The Employment Ministry has set up an armed team to rescue  
enslaved men, women and children, said Veja magazine, which cited 
previously undisclosed ministry figures. 
</P>
<P>
	The team targets the poor central and northern Brazilian states  
of Mato Grosso, Mato Grosso do Sul, Maranhao and Para, where 
unemployed workers are attracted to farms by offers of work. 
</P>
<P>
	Some farm owners force the people to work as long as 15 hours a  
day at unpaid manual labor and threaten them with violence, even 
death, if they try to leave, said Veja, Brazil's largest news 
magazine. 
</P>
<P>
	Though slavery was officially abolished in Brazil in 1888,  
President Fernando Henrique Cardoso admitted in 1995 that slave 
labor continued and vowed to combat it. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1998, a farm owner in Para state was given a 2 1/2-year  
suspended prison sentence for keeping slaves. A second farm owner, 
accused of enslaving 220 workers in the same state, is currently on 
trial, the magazine said. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	MEXICO CITY (AP) -- A leader of a religious sect was shot to  
death while riding in his pickup truck, Mexican newspapers reported 
Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	Ausencio Velazquez Huerta, a leader of ``The New Jerusalem''  
sect, was shot twice Saturday near Puruaran, in the western state 
of Michoacan. There have been no arrests. 
</P>
<P>
	The state attorney general's office said Velazquez Huerta was  
returning from a shopping trip when a man jumped out and fired six 
times into the truck, striking Velazquez Huerta twice, the 
newspaper Reforma reported. 
</P>
<P>
	In June, more than 300 people were expelled from the community  
for not complying with the sect's rules. It was not known if the 
shooting was related to the expulsions. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	SAN SALVADOR, El Salvador (AP) -- San Salvador's cathedral has  
reopened almost 13 years after being damaged in an earthquake, but 
more work needs to be done on the building, the auxiliary bishop 
said Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	Thousands of people attended the first public Mass on Sunday,  
two days after the cathedral formally reopened. 
</P>
<P>
	The 43-year-old cathedral in the center of the city was badly  
damaged during an October 1986 earthquake that killed hundreds of 
Salvadorans. The high cost of the repairs -- $5 million -- slowed the 
reconstruction. 
</P>
<P>
	Much work still needs to be done and church leaders hope to  
finish by the end of 2000, auxiliary bishop Gregorio Rosa Chavez 
told reporters. Workers must still install furniture, frame 
pictures, and decorate. 
</P>
<P>
	Archbishop Oscar Arnulfo Romero is buried in a special crypt in  
the cathedral. Romero, who criticized abuses by the Salvadoran 
military during the country's civil war, was killed March 24, 1980, 
while celebrating Mass in a church in a northern part of San 
Salvador, the capital 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	MEXICO CITY (AP) -- The body of a federal police subcommander in  
the border city of Reynosa was found Sunday near the Rio Grande and 
police believe he was killed in a clash with drug traffickers, the 
government news agency Notimex reported. 
</P>
<P>
	The body of Jaime Gutierrez Arreola was found at a recreational  
center in the city, across the border from McAllen, Texas, state 
police commander Juan Jose Muniz Salinas told Notimex. 
</P>
<P>
	He said that a driver had reported hearing a shootout at the  
recreational center and that a bullet had struck his car. 
</P>
<P>
	He said two four-wheel drive vehicles were found nearby later,  
both with several bullet holes. 
</P>
</TEXT>
