<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Gonzaga Looks Forward to Next Year </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SPOKANE, Wash. (AP) -- Gonzaga's Richie Frahm may get his wish --  
but the looming question is whether his coach will be with him next 
season. 
</P>
<P>
	``I want to go out like this next year, too,'' the junior guard  
told 500 Gonzaga fans who gathered on campus Saturday night to 
greet the Bulldogs on their return from the NCAA West Region finals 
in Phoenix. 
</P>
<P>
	Gonzaga's Cinderella run to the Elite Eight may have been  
unfathomable at the start of this season. But a return trip isn't 
out of the question because the Bulldogs are losing just three 
seniors to graduation. 
</P>
<P>
	The uncertainty is the future of coach Dan Monson, who may be  
lured away from the small Jesuit-run university by bigger schools 
with budgets that dwarf Gonzaga's $3.2 million in annual athletics 
spending. 
</P>
<P>
	Schools expressing interest so far include Washington State --  
just 75 miles south of Spokane in Pullman -- and San Diego State. 
</P>
<P>
	But it may take more than money to send Monson packing. After  
the Bulldogs' 67-62 loss to Connecticut on Saturday, Monson said he 
has a strong attachment to Gonzaga. 
</P>
<P>
	``This (season) certainly makes it tougher, but it's going to be  
tough for me to leave anyway because it's a great group of kids, 
it's a university I believe in and it's an administration that's 
supportive,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	The 37-year-old spent nine years as a Gonzaga assistant under  
Dan Fitzgerald, who hand-picked Monson as his successor when he 
stepped down at the end of the 1997 season. 
</P>
<P>
	In Monson's 11 years with Gonzaga, the Bulldogs have won 20 or  
more games six times and twice advanced to the NCAA tournament. The 
team, which plays in the low-profile West Coast Conference, 
finished with a school-record 28 victories this season against 
seven losses. 
</P>
<P>
	In deciding his future, Monson has said he may consider the  
experiences of his father. Don Monson had a successful run coaching 
Idaho before having a more difficult time at Oregon, a bigger 
school that fired him in 1992. 
</P>
<P>
	The three graduating seniors are starters Quentin Hall and  
Jeremy Eaton and reserve Mike Leasure. 
</P>
<P>
	Key returning players include current juniors Frahm and Matt  
Santangelo, who made Gonzaga one of the nation's top outside 
shooting threats this season. 
</P>
<P>
	Also back will be starting forward Casey Calvary and key  
reserves Axel Dench , Mark Spink and Ryan Floyd. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
