<DOCNO> APW19990321.0077 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-21 16:12:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 7 p.m. EST  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Yugoslav General Says Troops Ready  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- A top Yugoslav Army general said today that  
the country's troops are prepared ``to repel any aggression against 
our country.'' That statement was made just hours before the U.S. 
makes a final diplomatic effort at peace by sending special U.S. 
envoy Richard Holbrooke to meet with Yugoslav President Slobodan 
Milosevic. Airstrikes are likely to follow if the talks end with 
Milosevic defiant on two counts: still refusing a Kosovo peace plan 
and persisting in pressing an offensive against outgunned Kosovo 
rebels. 

</P>
<P>
	Statements on Train Crash May Conflict  
</P>
<P>
	BOURBONNAIS, Ill. (AP) -- Witnesses to the deadly Amtrak train  
crash may have given conflicting statements about whether a 
steel-laden truck was on the tracks before warning signals and 
crossing gates activated. ``We have not been able to completely 
reconcile the statements that are possibly conflicting,'' said 
National Transportation Safety Board spokesman Jamie Finch. He 
would not comment on what the possible conflicts were. Eleven 
people were killed and more than 100 injured in when the Amtrak 
train crashed into the truck on March 15. 

</P>
<P>
	Chechen Assassination Try Kills 1  
</P>
<P>
	GROZNY, Russia (AP) -- A mine exploded near Chechen President  
Aslan Maskhadov's motorcade today in an assassination attempt while 
he was returning to his residence. Maskhadov was not hurt. One 
person was killed and eight were wounded by the radio-controlled 
device, said the president's press secretary, according to the 
Interfax news agency. It was the second explosion to rock the 
troubled Caucasus region in just three days. At least 51 people 
were killed in an explosion Friday at a crowded market in 
Vladikavkaz. 

</P>
<P>
	OPEC Urges Compliance With Oil Cuts  
</P>
<P>
	VIENNA, Austria (AP) -- OPEC ministers eager to end a global oil  
glut expressed hope today that oil-exporting nations would abide by 
production cuts designed to slash total output by more than 2 
million barrels a day. The new quotas, which are to begin April 1, 
would remain in effect for a full year. Under the deal reached at 
The Hague, Saudi Arabia, which currently produces more than 8 
million barrels a day, will take the biggest cut -- 585,000 barrels. 
Formal approval of the production cuts is expected in a meeting 
between leaders Tuesday. 

</P>
<P>
	Gas Prices Soar About 8 1/2 Cents  
</P>
<P>
	SAN ANTONIO, Texas (AP) -- Gasoline prices experienced their  
biggest jump in nearly a decade, rising about 8 1/2 cents per gallon 
at the pump over the past two weeks as global changes reduced a 
supply glut, an analyst said today. The increase was only the 
second since September and followed a half-cent hike recorded two 
weeks ago. 

</P>
<P>
	NY Gov. Criticized by GOP Hopefuls  
</P>
<P>
	ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) -- New York Gov. George Pataki came under fire  
today from two contenders for the Republican presidential 
nomination over his call to remove the anti-abortion plank from the 
GOP's national platform. The pro-choice Pataki is eyeing the race 
himself. Conservative commentator Pat Buchanan, appearing on ABC's 
``This Week'' program, said removing the anti-abortion plank from 
the platform would ``start a civil war'' within the GOP. 

</P>
<P>
	Oscars To Be Awarded Tonight  
</P>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- The contest between a World War II combat  
movie and one about Shakespeare's early manhood reaches a climax 
this evening with the Academy Awards. After last year's blowout by 
``Titanic,'' the movie crowd seems to welcome a real race this 
year: between Steven Spielberg's unrelenting ``Saving Private 
Ryan'' and the romantic Elizabethan fantasy, ``Shakespeare in 
Love.'' The other candidates for best picture are ``Elizabeth,'' 
``Life Is Beautiful'' and ``The Thin Red Line.'' 

</P>
<P>
	Rematch Set for Holyfield-Lewis  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Evander Holyfield and Lennox Lewis have agreed  
to fight again for the undisputed heavyweight championship. Now 
promoter Don King must decide on a date and find a site willing to 
pay millions for the rematch. King said today that both fighters 
want the bout in September, and that both would be guaranteed $15 
million for the rematch. 

</P>
<P>
	Blue Devils in Final Four  
</P>
<P>
	EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. (AP) -- Duke surged into the Final Four  
with a 85-64 victory over sixth-seeded Temple in the East Regional 
final today. The Blue Devils extended their school-record winning 
streak to 31 games. They will be making their 12th Final Four 
appearance -- the eighth under coach Mike Krzyzewski. Duke's Trajan 
Langdon finished 5-for-6 from 3-point range and had 23 points, 
while Elton Brand had 21 points and eight rebounds. The loss 
deprived Owls coach John Chaney of his first trip to the Final 
Four. 


</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by BRADLEY BROOKS  
</P>
